A Data Science Pipeline Tutorial on Fertility¶

In this tutorial, I will be exploring a fertility dataset based on WHO standards on sperm, which are diagnosed normal (N) or altered (O).

Author: Diana Shin
Version: May 16th, 2021

Introduction¶

Welcome to my data science pipeline tutorial, where I will be showing how to work with data from collection to analysis. The fertility dataset I will be using is from the University of California, Irvine Machine Learning Repository available here: UCI Machine Learning Repository. This is a great repository to try out exploratory data analysis, and you can filter out datasets so that they are small and have anywhere from 10, to 100 or more columns/variables.

I recommend a few datasets that are interesting and have different types of data (categorical, numerical, words, etc):

  • Tic-tac-toe, categorical play data that fits decision trees: Tic-Tac-Toe Endgame Data Set
  • Credit approval, a mix of categorical data and numerical data prime for exploratory data analysis: Credit Approval Data Set
  • NSF research abstracts, a bag of words of various abstracts that received NSF awards, I recommend using the Natural Language Processing Toolkit (nltk) NLTK Book with this project: NSF Research Award Abstracts 1990-2003 Data Set

This tutorial will be following the data science pipeline:
Data Collection
Data Processing
Exploratory Analysis and Data Visualization
Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML
Insight and Policy Decision

Motivation¶

For this data science pipeline tutorial, I chose this dataset because it had a mix of numerical and categorical data. In addition, it is an interesting topic to explore. Typically, we hear about fertility, but how much do we know about it? This dataset has a collection of approximately 100 semen samples from volunteers based on WHO standards, with variables ranging from their sitting and drinking habits, whether their fertility is normal, etc. From a CDC statistic survey in 2018, there were about 4 million births in 2014. This tutorial could be helpful in exploring what could be helpful to the millions of people wanting to have a child. Let's explore!

Data Collection¶

To get the data from the UCI Machine Learning Repository, you could download the data from the Data Folder link, or you can use the os library to grab the data automatically. I am running on Linux, so I will be using wget to grab the dataset. There are lots of commands to work with your system as you grab and handle data, so I recommend looking at SS64 if you are on a Linux system to get familiar with the commands used in this tutorial.

Before we start downloading the data used, I noticed that the column descriptions on the UCI website are not really complete, take the number of hours sitting what is 0-1 supposed to represent? Sometimes, you have to do more research about the data you are working with before you start to work with it if the descriptions are not fully present. So, I found the person who contributed this database to UCI and his related paper in Oxford Academic at Semen Parameters Can Be Predicted from Environmental Factors and Lifestyle Using Artificial Intelligence Methods, where in fact the number of hours was scaled on 0-1 based on a min max of 0-16 hours per day. Here is a complete list of the columns and how they were normalized in this dataset:

Feel free to refer to this throughout the tutorial for information about the columns in this data set.

We can see that the file does not contain column names, but just comma separated values per row/observation. Looking back at the UCI website, we can see that the real columns are

  • Season in which the analysis was performed. 1) winter, 2) spring, 3) Summer, 4) fall. (-1, -0.33, 0.33, 1)
  • Age at the time of analysis. 18-36 (0, 1)
  • Childish diseases (ie , chicken pox, measles, mumps, polio) 1) yes, 2) no. (0, 1)
  • Accident or serious trauma 1) yes, 2) no. (0, 1)
  • Surgical intervention 1) yes, 2) no. (0, 1)
  • High fevers in the last year 1) less than three months ago, 2) more than three months ago, 3) no. (-1, 0, 1)
  • Frequency of alcohol consumption 1) several times a day, 2) every day, 3) several times a week, 4) once a week, 5) hardly ever or never (0, 1)
  • Smoking habit 1) never, 2) occasional 3) daily. (-1, 0, 1)
  • Number of hours spent sitting per day ene-16 (0, 1)
  • Output: Diagnosis normal (N), altered (O)

It is always a good idea to take a look at the data file, so you can load it into a database software like Pandas properly. For example, below we will be using the Pandas function read_csv to read this comma separated data, but we want to set the header to None so we don't accidently set an observation as the column names.

Here is a bad example of loading in the data (not considering that the column names are not in the comma separated text file):

However, it is always important to check the data itself, for example, below I will be checking the data types of each column and also be checking for any missing data. We want to do this because we want to be familiar with our data and also because we want to make sure we are careful in our analysis if there is missing data.

We can see that the data have mostly the correct types, however, the only one that is troublesome is the diagnosis column. Pandas actually has a a function pandas.convert_dtypes() which actually converts the columns to their ideal types ex. float, etc and also corrects any missing data like NaN to pd.NA. For example, we want diagnosis to be a string because it has N/O as its classfication values, not necessarily 'object'.

Exploring numerical variables¶

Exploring how age and hours relate
We often want to see relationships not only with the "end goal" data like diagnosis, but we also want to learn about other aspects of our data possible correlations. It could provide insight to other lines of research this dataset presents. Below, we are going to explore how age and hours relate by making a scatter plot and plotting different regressions. Later on in this tutorial, we will run statistical tests on the relationship we find.

Why did we plot without the regression you may ask? It is important to first take a look at the data and see if it looks "linear", "quadratic" etc because you don't want to assume anything about the data before you even look at it. ' You could fall prey to confirmation bias if you think it works and don't consider other options. That being said, this data does look fairly linear or possible a very very slow logarithmic function, but let's try both to see which fits better!

In [13]:
# Linear Regression

# Can run NumPy's polyfit with 1 degree on it, it is a least squares regression.
p = np.poly1d(np.polyfit(age_hours_df['age'], age_hours_df['hours_sitting_day'], 1))
# Setting up a linspace for plotting
xp = np.linspace(0.4, 1.2, 100)

# Plot with xp (linspace) and the predicted values
age_hours_plot.plot(xp, p(xp), label=p, color='green')
age_hours_plot.legend()

In [14]:
# Logarithmic Regression

# Wrangle data to pass into function
x_vals = list()
y_vals = list()

for index,data in age_hours_df.iterrows():
    x_vals.append(data['age'])
    y_vals.append(data['hours_sitting_day'])
In [15]:
# Run fit,
# Sometimes the function you want is not readily encoded
# for you in a library. So, you can use scipy with your own function
# that you want to fit.
scipy.optimize.curve_fit(lambda t,a,b: a+b*np.log(t),  x_vals,  y_vals)
# y  0.20271423 -0.48869888 log(x)

# Create a function to handle plotting (similar to p above)
def log_func(x):
    return 0.20271423 - 0.48869888*np.log(x)
In [16]:
# Logistic Regression Plot

# Defining our linspace
xp = np.linspace(0.4, 1.2, 100)

# Log prediction output list
ly  = list()

# Grab the log predictions
for x in xp:
    ly.append(log_func(x))
    

# Plot as before, adding the function to our legend
age_hours_plot.plot(xp, ly, label='y  0.20271423 -0.48869888 log(x)', color='red')
age_hours_plot.legend()

fig
Out[16]:

We can see that there is not much difference between the logistic and linear graphs, but the logistic one does seem to fit the data better in this section.

Also, the logistic graph will never cross zero, whereas the linear one will, in this sense the logistic graph is a better representation of real life on the high end of age because you cannot sit for negative hours. However, it is also not very realistic near 0 because it would approach infinity whereas the linear approximation will not approach infinity but instead an intercept point.

Depending on your purposes, you could be fine choosing the linear model for a situation like this, but note that the logistic model is a better representation of the real-world on the right-end and the linear model is a better representation of the real-world on the left-end.

Another thing to note is that there is a cluster of abnormal semen around 0.7 in normalized age and 0.4 in normalized hours sitting per day. Maybe we can learn from it later on in our data science pipeline!

For the purposes of this data science tutorial, we will be continuing with the linear approximation because it is a simpler approximation, it fits our data visually, and it is easier to work with hypothesis tests.

Exploring how age relates to diagnosis
We can actually make a dot plot / number line plot with matplotlib with a little effort! I learned a lot from this StackOverflow post StackOverflow Dot Plot to make the below cell. We want to consider how age could possibly relate to diagnosis, while also getting a better sense of our data. Making a dot plot could be helpful in this and is feasible without having to make bins like with a histogram.

In [17]:
# Let's make a number line / dot plot of the age and see how it relates to diagnosis
values, counts = np.unique(age_hours_df['age'], return_counts=True)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))

# Count how many are N/O diagnosis by grabbing N counts
diag = list()
for val in values:
    N = age_hours_df.loc[(age_hours_df['age'] == val) & (age_hours_df['diagnosis'] == 'N')].any(axis=1).sum()
    diag.append(N)
    
# Added to legend boolean variable: because
# we are runnign plot in a for loop, we only want to add the label to the legend
# if it is not already there.
legend_fulfilled = False
    
# In this for loop we will be going through the values
# plotting based on N/O where diag is the number of 'N' diags
for value, count, diag in zip(values, counts, diag): 
    if legend_fulfilled == False:
        plt.plot([value]*(diag), list(range(diag)), 'go', ms=14, linestyle='', label='N')
        plt.plot([value]*(count - diag), list(range(count - diag)), 'mo', ms=14, linestyle='', label='O')
        legend_fulfilled = True
    else:
        plt.plot([value]*(diag), list(range(diag)), 'go', ms=14, linestyle='')
        plt.plot([value]*(count - diag), list(range(count - diag)), 'mo', ms=14, linestyle='')
    
# Make it cleaner by removing the spines of the graph
for spine in ['top', 'right', 'left']:
    ax.spines[spine].set_visible(False)

# Add context to the graph
ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)
ax.set_ylim(-0.5, max(counts))
ticks = list(values)
ticks.sort()
ax.set_xticks(ticks)
ax.tick_params(axis='x', pad=5, labelsize=12)
ax.set_title('Dot Plot of Normalized Age and Corresponding Diagnosis')
ax.legend()

plt.show()

What we can learn from it:
We can see that there seems to be a cluster around 0.67 and 0.69 of altered sperm (not normal). This corresponds to 0.67*36 and .69*36 which is 24.12 and 24.84. But! We have to notice that these age groups are more represented in the data set, though still not super tall like 0.56, so if you have more people you will have more instances of not normal sperm. But this is something to take note of because it is unusual!

Exploring categorical variables¶

In this section I will be grabbing sub data frames by their diagnosis, called N_sub and O-sub to get different counts / proportions of the diagnosis in relative dataframes to our categorical variables. Sometimes, grabbing sub dataframes gives us more freedom in our code to wrangle with the data.

We are interested in grabbing separate dataframes and wrangling them because we want to see how different categories for each of our categorical variables could possibly affect diagnosis as normal or altered.

After working with the data, I then plotted each categorical variable and their normalized freqeuncies of N/O per category in a bar chart to visually see the distribution of the N/O diagnosis of sperm.

Why normalized, why approach it this way? Again we care about the distribution of the normal/altered sperm per category. Some categories will have more people in it than others, and can make us think that those categories have more weight just by the number of people. However, we want to see the distribution of N/Os which requires us to normalize based on # people per category to see percentages of normal and abnormal sperm in that category. In the bar charts below, consider what could happen if we didn't normalize our data beforehand.

# We are going to repeat the process of what we did above as for other categorical variables in this dataset.

# Childish diseases
childish_diseases_N = N_sub[['childish_diseases', 'diagnosis']].groupby('childish_diseases').count()
childish_diseases_N.columns = ['N']
childish_diseases_O = O_sub[['childish_diseases', 'diagnosis']].groupby('childish_diseases').count()
childish_diseases_O.columns = ['O']
childish_diseases = childish_diseases_N.join(childish_diseases_O)
childish_diseases['total'] = childish_diseases['N'] + childish_diseases['O']
childish_diseases['N_normal'] = childish_diseases['N'] / childish_diseases['total']
childish_diseases['O_normal'] = childish_diseases['O'] / childish_diseases['total']

# Accidents / Serious Trauma
accident_trauma_N = N_sub[['accident_trauma', 'diagnosis']].groupby('accident_trauma').count()
accident_trauma_N.columns = ['N']
accident_trauma_O = O_sub[['accident_trauma', 'diagnosis']].groupby('accident_trauma').count()
accident_trauma_O.columns = ['O']
accident_trauma = accident_trauma_N.join(accident_trauma_O)
accident_trauma['total'] = accident_trauma['N'] + accident_trauma['O']
accident_trauma['N_normal'] = accident_trauma['N'] / accident_trauma['total']
accident_trauma['O_normal'] = accident_trauma['O'] / accident_trauma['total']

surgical_intervention['total'] = surgical_intervention['N'] + surgical_intervention['O']

Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML¶

Analysis of our Visualizations and Models
In this section: I want to talk about some things we noticed from our Exploratory Data Analysis.

In terms of relationships between our numerical variables of age and number of hours sitting in a day, we found that there was approximately a linear relationship between age and the number of hours you sit in a day. Although this insight is separate from the actual diagnosis, it is still interesting to note how age and a behavior like hours sitting relates.

In terms of possible relationships between age and diagnosis of normal or abnormal sperm around 24 years old, there was a larger portion of abnormal sperm compared to other age groups. Between hours sitting in a day and diagnosis, we didn't really see a correlation between the two.

Impact on diagnosis:

Among numerical variables: maybe age has an impact?

Now, onto our categorical variables. Earlier in our Exploratory Data Analysis, we analyzed if there were possible connections between the catgories for a particular variable and the diagnosis of sperm (normalized to be percentages out of 100). Among our visualizations, we found that season of analysis, serious accidents or trauma, high fever in the last year and alcohol consumption seemed to have the most affect on diagnosis of sperm.

Hypothesis Testing
We did a series of analyses above based on our EDA, but let's try to run hypothesis tests on what we thought to see if our insight is significant. I recommend looking at hypothesis tests you can do on various data science websites, here is one that I will be referencing for this tutorial: Determining the Statistical Test to Use fo Hypothesis Testing.

Here are the series of hypothesis tests we will be conducting:

  • Hypothesis test of linear correlation between age and hours sitting (aside but interesting to see)
  • Hypothesis test of age and diagnosis
  • Hypothesis test of season of analysis and diagnosis
  • Hypothesis test of serious accidents or trauma and diagnosis
  • Hypothesis test of high fever in the last year and diagnosis
  • Hypothesis test of alcohol consumption and diagnosis

In the tests I will be following a standard 5% significance level.

Hypothesis test of linear correlation between age and hours sitting (aside but interesting to see)
Below, I will be using the statsmodels library in order to conduct a hypothesis test on our data. Statsmodels runs the regression and t-test for us so we can just analyze the output. We want to run a hypothesis test to see if what we encountered was due to chance or not on a 5% significance level.

This means for every one unit change in age (we did it on normalized, reminder from 0-36 yrs old) the odds of a normal diagnosis increases by 2.8611, and the associated p value is approximately zero, so we reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between age and diagnosis. However, it is important to note that this model may not be the best because of the linear assumption between age and diagnosis, which may not be the best.
In fact, this test for telling the different between groups is not even recommended or even really correct. We want to test the difference between different samples and see if the different between the two is significant.

Perhaps a better test rather than this logitmodel would be a two independent samples t-test where you want to compare the means of two normally distributed independent groups. From our numerline plot above, our data looks approximately normal for N/O groups, so let's try this model/hypothesis test instead to do a different hypothesis test.

In [36]:
# Luckily, we already grabbed N/O groups while doing our visualization
group1 = N_sub['age'].values
group2 = O_sub['age'].values

test_results = sm.stats.ttest_ind(group1,group2,alternative="two-sided",usevar="unequal")
test_results[1] # Print only the pvalue, other values are tstat and df
Out[36]:
0.20746413483532258

Here we found that the p-value is much higher than 0 in a previous hypothesis test. We got p = 0.207, which with a 5% significance level that there is not a statistically signficant difference between age for the Normal and Abnormal sperm groups. Always make sure that you are doing a proper test for your purposes.

Let's continue with our series of hypothesis tests, moving onto our categorical variables:

Hypothesis test of season of analysis and diagnosis
Hypothesis test of serious accidents or trauma and diagnosis
Hypothesis test of high fever in the last year and diagnosis
Hypothesis test of alcohol consumption and diagnosis

Now, I am going to move on to hypothesis tests of
$ categorical\text{ }variable \text{ vs } diagnosis$

Because we are doing categorical vs a categorical, we should be doing a chi-squared test to see how likely it is that any observed difference between the sets arose by chance. We want to see if the sets are really independent, or that diagnosis does or does not rely on the season of analysis, serious accidents, etc. We want to use Pearson's chi square test for this purpose because we care about the differences between groups. So, we will use chi2_contingency from the statsmodels library. Here is further reading on Pearson's chi-square test of independence: Pearson's Chi-square Test.

Alternative choice note: you may possibly be thinking why not use chisquare from the statsmodels library, and that is valid. We could potentially do a chisquare test by saying that the observed values should be 50/50 for each diagnosis N/O in each group. However, that is not what we are looking for. We want to see if N/O depends on our categories for a particular variable, not if they are different than expected values per se.

Hypothesis test of season of analysis and diagnosis
Below, I will be using the statsmodels library to conduct a hypothesis test.

In [37]:
# Chi square test, we want the second element of the array
# because that returns our p-value.
obs = season_of_analysis[['O_normal', 'N_normal']].values
g, p, dof, expctd = scipy.stats.chi2_contingency(obs)
p
Out[37]:
0.9754795561167672

Our p-value is 0.9754795561167672 which tells us that season of analysis is actually not significant.

Machine Learning
Even though we only found one significant statistic high fever in the last year, we can still try to build a model to predict diagnosis of normal and abnormal sperm. Because we are trying to predict a yes/no or normal/abnormal sperm, we should use a classification model. One such model we could use is a decision tree! This is a simple classification model that depending on certain variables, it will branch off into separate branches, eventually reaching a leaf classifying the sperm type. We can use SKLearn to generate a decision tree for us and analyze the output compared to test data.

How to interpret the classification report:
For more mathematical definitions with the report, please refer to an artcile like Understanding the Classification Report in SKLearn
Precision, what percentage of our classifications were correct?

  • In terms of N / normal sperm, we were about 96% correct.
  • In term of O / abnormal sperm, we were 17% correct.

Recall, what percentage of positives did you catch from the test data?

  • In terms of N / normal sperm, we caught about 82%.
  • In terms of O / abnormal sperm, we caught 50%.

As a rule of thumb, the weighted average of F1 should be used to compare classifier models, not global accuracy.

Our f1 weighted average is about 84% which is nice! This may be good for trying things out, but if you want better accuracy in the real world you may have to play around with parameters.

Note: The f1-score is a combination of precision and recall.

Insight and Policy Decision¶

We won't be making any policy decisions here, but we will be making some insights about the data we have encountered in this data science pipeline tutorial.

Regarding a connection between our numerical variables: age and hours sitting in a day, we found that there was a significant negative linear relationship between the two at least with the ages covered in this survey of 18-36 year old people.

Fertility insights
It is quite surprising that we found the only significant variable to be accident or serious trauma, with more abnormal sperm found in the group with no accidents or serious trauma. Perhaps this data is skewed, especially with so few participants, or it could be that something about having a serious accident or trauma really has something to do with sperm. There is one, thing, it does warrant more investigation. In data science, you can do research and analyze data and also go back in the pipeline. This is an instance where possibly going back would be helpful, was it something with the participants themselves, or could we have done different analysis? Could we have asked this question better to see what could have happened? There are endless questions, and sometimes we have to keep on repeating different parts of the pipeline to get our answers.

As for our model, we were able to predict with about ~80% accuracy of a normal or abnormal sperm diagnosis. We tried to avoid overfitting our data by setting our minimum leaves to 2. However, that doesn't mean we were that successful. Plus, it doesn't help that our test data was imbalanced, partially because so many of the patients had normal sperm out of the 100. Perhaps more data collection can be done here.

Were we able to get great insights? Maybe, but there are more tests to be done!
